In addition, we take a lock so that our Send() calls preserve the IDuplexSessionChannel in-order guarantee, and so that calls to the underlying socket are synchronized correctly.

overrides On[Begin]Open and On[Begin]Close to control the lifetime if its listen socket. In OnOpen, we create a socket to listen on IP_ANY. More advanced implementations could create a second socket to listen on IPv6 as well. They could also allow the IP Address to be specified in the hostname.

When a new socket is accepted, we initialize a server-side channel with this socket. All the I/O is already implemented in the base class, so this channel is simply responsible for initializing the socket.

To set up, build, and run the sample
To run this sample you will need WSE 3.0 and the WSE TcpSyncStockService sample. You can download WSE 3.0 from MSDN
Once you've installed WSE 3.0, do the following steps:
Open the TcpSyncStockService in Visual Studio
Set the StockService project as the startup project

Open StockService.cs in the StockService project and comment out the [Policy] attribute on the StockService class. This will disable security from the sample. While WCF can interoperate with WSE 3.0 secure endpoints, we are disabling security to keep this sample focused on the custom TCP transport
Press F5 to start the TcpSyncStockService. The service will start in a new console window
Open this TCP transport sample in Visual Studio
Update the "hostname" variable to match the machine name running the TcpSyncStockService
Press F5 to start the TCP transport sample

The TCP transport test client will start in a new console window and will wait for you to press Enter. Once you press Enter, the client will request stock quotes from the service then display the results in its console window
